<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<section xml:id="sec_what_is_robotics" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Introduction to Robotics</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Robotics is an interdisciplinary field that combines mechanical engineering, 
      electrical engineering, computer science, and artificial intelligence to design, 
      build, and program machines capable of performing tasks autonomously or 
      semi-autonomously.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_definition">
    <title>Defining a Robot</title>
    <p>
      A <term>robot</term> is a programmable machine that can sense its environment, 
      make decisions based on that sensory information, and act upon the environment 
      to accomplish specific tasks. Unlike simple automated machines, robots have the 
      ability to adapt their behavior based on changing conditions.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Key characteristics of robots include:
      <ul>
        <li><em>Sensing:</em> The ability to perceive the environment through sensors</li>
        <li><em>Processing:</em> The capability to process sensor data and make decisions</li>
        <li><em>Actuation:</em> The means to physically interact with the environment</li>
        <li><em>Autonomy:</em> Some degree of independent operation without constant human control</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_history">
    <title>Brief History of Robotics</title>
    <p>
      The word "robot" comes from the Czech word "robota," meaning forced labor, 
      first used in Karel Čapek's 1920 play <em>R.U.R. (Rossum's Universal Robots)</em>.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Modern robotics has evolved through several key milestones:
      <ul>
        <li><em>1954:</em> George Devol invented the first digitally operated programmable robot, 
            called Unimate</li>
        <li><em>1961:</em> Unimate was installed on a General Motors assembly line, marking 
            the beginning of industrial robotics</li>
        <li><em>1997:</em> NASA's Sojourner rover explored Mars, demonstrating autonomous 
            planetary exploration</li>
        <li><em>2000s-present:</em> Explosion of service robots, autonomous vehicles, and 
            AI-powered robotic systems</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_applications">
    <title>Applications of Robotics</title>
    <p>
      Robots are used in a wide variety of applications across many industries:
    </p>

    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>Manufacturing</title>
        <p>Industrial robots perform welding, painting, assembly, and material handling 
           with high precision and consistency.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Healthcare</title>
        <p>Surgical robots assist doctors with minimally invasive procedures, while 
           rehabilitation robots help patients recover motor functions.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Exploration</title>
        <p>Robots explore environments too dangerous or remote for humans, from deep 
           ocean trenches to distant planets.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Service and Domestic</title>
        <p>Vacuum cleaners, lawn mowers, and delivery robots are becoming increasingly 
           common in our daily lives.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Transportation</title>
        <p>Autonomous vehicles and drones are revolutionizing how we move people and 
           goods.</p>
      </li>
    </dl>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_challenges">
    <title>Challenges in Robotics</title>
    <p>
      Despite remarkable progress, robotics still faces several significant challenges:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>Perception in Unstructured Environments:</em> Understanding complex, 
            changing real-world scenes remains difficult</li>
        <li><em>Manipulation:</em> Grasping and manipulating diverse objects with 
            human-like dexterity is extremely challenging</li>
        <li><em>Human-Robot Interaction:</em> Creating natural, safe, and effective 
            interfaces between humans and robots</li>
        <li><em>Generalization:</em> Building robots that can adapt to new tasks and 
            environments without extensive reprogramming</li>
        <li><em>Energy and Power:</em> Developing efficient power systems for long-term 
            autonomous operation</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      Understanding what robotics is and its applications provides the context for 
      diving deeper into how robots work. In the following sections, we'll explore 
      the subsystems that make up a robot and how they work together to enable 
      intelligent, autonomous behavior.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</section>
